'''AthenaPlus''' is a CIP best practice network started in March 2013 which aims to facilitate access to networks of cultural heritage, enrich metadata, as well as improve search, retrieval and re-use of [[Europeana]]’s content by enhancing multilingual terminology management and the export/publication tool.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.emuziejai.lt/athena-plus/|title=AthenaPlus – Access to Cultural Heritage Networks for Europeana - Muziejinių vertybių skaitmeninimas|website=www.emuziejai.lt|language=lt-LT|access-date=2018-10-15}}</ref> By the end of the project, AthenaPlus will contribute more than 3.6 millions of metadata records to [[Europeana]], from both public and private sectors, focusing mainly on museums content.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://cordis.europa.eu/project/rcn/191937_en.html|title=Access to cultural heritage networks for Europeana {{!}} Projects {{!}} CIP {{!}} CORDIS {{!}} European Commission|work=CORDIS {{!}} European Commission|access-date=2018-10-15}}</ref> In addition to enabling access to cultural heritage, AthenaPlus is also focused on creative use of content, and adapting data to users with different needs by means of tools that support the development of virtual exhibitions, tourist and didactic applications.<ref>I. Ehrlicher, M. Hagedorn-Saupe, S. Linnemann, S. Rohde Enslin (Stiftung Preussischer Kulturbesitz Berlin). ''Logo, corporate message, project website, shared dissemination plan, guidelines for Partners''. 2013, p. 4.</ref>
==Movio== [http://www.movio.beniculturali.it MOVIO] is an [[open source]] [[Content management system|CMS]], a kit of tools<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2014-01-01|title=MOVIO: A Toolkit for Creating Curated Digital Exhibitions|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1877050914013660|journal=Procedia Computer Science|language=en|volume=38|pages=28–33|doi=10.1016/j.procs.2014.10.006|issn=1877-0509}}</ref>, developed within the AthenaPlus project, which enables web content creation. [http://www.movio.beniculturali.it MOVIO] has a semantic approach; it can be defined as a SCMS (Semantic Content Management System) as well. It enables building online digital exhibitions targeted to different audiences and aims to enable long term accessibility to the mass of knowledge generated by temporary exhibitions that, for their nature, have a limited life span.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mw2016.museumsandtheweb.com/glami/movio-on-line-virtual-exhibitions/|title=MOVIO On Line Virtual Exhibitions {{!}} MW2016: Museums and the Web 2016|website=mw2016.museumsandtheweb.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-10-15}}</ref> The content is shaped using different tools integrated in the software: media archive, [[ontology]] builder, [[storytelling|storyteller]], different types of image galleries, hotspots, maps, timeline, etc. The project was initiated by the [[Istituto Centrale per il Catalogo Unico|Central Institute for the Union Catalogue of the Italian Libraries]] (ICCU), a body of the Ministry, developed by [http://www.gruppometa.it/en/home GruppoMeta], and owing to a grant of the Fondazione Telecom Italia 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dedale.info/_objets/medias/autres/mca-iccu-berlinheritagesummit-2018-1140.pdf|title=Creating digital exhibitions with MOVIO|last=Natale|first=Maria Teresa|date=|website=dedale|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> [http://www.gruppometa.it/en/movio MOVIO] is released under MIT license that allows the widest possible reuse of software.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=MOVIO: A semantic content management and valorisation approach for archives and cultural institutions|url=http://www.girona.cat/web/ica2014/ponents/textos/id234.pdf|journal=|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> The source code has been published on [https://github.com/GruppoMeta/Movio GIT-HUB].
==Partners== The consortium is composed of 40 partners from 21 member countries:<ref>[http://www.athenaplus.eu/index.php?en/153/partners-and-contributors "Partners and Contributors"], AthenaPlus, 4 March 2015</ref>
